H0.text: Semipermeable is the term that best describes the capability of a cell membrane to allow some molecules to move freely across the membrane while restricting others.

H1.text: Impervious describes the capability of a cell membrane to allow some molecules to move freely across the membrane while restricting others.

H2.text: Resilient is the term that best describes the capability of a cell membrane to allow some molecules to move freely across the membrane while restricting others.

H3.text: Unyielding is the term that best describes a cell membraneâ€™s capability to allow some molecules to move freely across it while restricting others.

A4.text: Biological membranes are selectively permeable, with the passage of molecules controlled by facilitated diffusion, passive transport or active transport regulated by proteins embedded in the membrane.

A5.text: A phospholipid bilayer is an example of a biological semipermeable membrane.
